description.plain:
“Low” is the debut single by Flo Rida, from his debut album Mail on Sunday. it was also the soundtrack to the 2008 film Step Up 2: The Streets.

Its catchy, club oriented Southern hip-hop influences made it the longest-running number-one single in the US in 2008, besides reaching number one for the week of December 30, 2007 – January 5, 2008.

The song contains strong sexual elements and references about dancing in the club. He refers to a sexy “shawty” who “stole the show” and made the club fall on their heels. Basically a club song with a groovy instrumental.

description.plain:
The second track from Flo Rida’s My House EP finds Flo doing what he does best: turning up under a poppy beat.

This track doesn’t find him in the club like some of his other tracks. It finds him, unsurprisingly, at his house. Regardless, we can still assume that it’s going down (for real).

The song was released as a single in October 2015. However, it didn’t reach its peak until March 2016. It peaked at #4, becoming the EP’s second top ten in the US.

Flo Rida and Sage The Gemini collaborate on “GDFR,” (Going Down For Real) which is a radio-friendly single that appears on Flo’s EP My House. It hit 8 in the US, becoming his first top ten since “I Cry” in 2012.

The song uses instrumental samples from LooKas' remix of “Low Rider” by War.

This song was also used as one of the theme songs for WWE’s Summerslam event in 2014.

songs.title: Right Round

description.plain:
“Right Round” is a song performed by American rapper Flo Rida from R.O.O.T.S., his second studio album. It was released to radio as the album’s lead single on January 27, 2009. Pop singer Kesha contributed guest vocals to the song, but was only credited internationally.

The song lyrically speaks of developing a crush on a woman at a strip club, while musically incorporating a sample of the 1984 Dead or Alive song “You Spin Me Round (Like a Record)” in its hook.

It was critically acclaimed and remained atop the Hot 100 for six consecutive weeks.

“Club Can’t Handle Me” is a song by Flo Rida featuring French DJ David Guetta. It was released as  the lead single of the Step Up 3D soundtrack album and is also included on Flo Rida’s third studio album, Only One Flo (Part 1).

The song topped the charts in Ireland, Poland, Portugal and the United Kingdom, and became a top five hit in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Germany, Belgium, The Netherlands and Finland. The music video was filmed in Los Angeles and directed by Marc Klasfeld.

Flo Rida said of their collaboration, “…[it] came about through E Class, who’s the CEO of Poe Boy Entertainment. He’s great friends with Timbaland. Normally you’d need $100,000 to get into the studio with Timbaland, but I found out he’s a fan of me, and he had to a favor for his brother E Class. So we were in the studio for four days. For a first time artist that’s unheard of. The first two days I acquainted with him and got to vibe with him, and he has a love for music, but at the same time me and him have in common, that we put God first. The last couple of days we came up with ‘Elevator’ and then we shot the video about a week and a half later.

songs.full_title: Wobble by Flo Rida
songs.title: Wobble

description.plain:
For My House’s fourth track, Flo RIda enlists Cook Classics Mike Caren, and a Little Willie John sample to make “Wobble”: a catchy, pop-rap song that’s about crushing and sex.

Flo isn’t known for his songs about crushes. Generally, they’re more innuendo-y, about being in a club, or both. There’s a first time for everything, though…

It’s interesting to note that at the time of its release, Flo was single, yet this song has themes of wanting to start a relationship. However, Flo does have writing credits on this song (albeit with four other people) so perhaps it’s based off of a real-life experience?

songs.title: Once In a Lifetime

description.plain:
“Once In a Lifetime” is the first track on Flo Rida’s seven-song EP My House. Allowing us a glimpse of his sentimental side, Flo reminisces about an ex-girl. The song is characterized by conspicuous Chipmunk-style chorus vocals.

Flo told ET Online:

This record is very heartfelt but at the same time, me growing up from the projects, I thought this was a record that could definitely represent something more real.

The song was released on March 3, 2015, some days before the EP dropped. It came with an official music video, which was filmed at the Martin Luther King Jr. Day parade in Miami, Florida.

songs.title: Turn Around (5, 4, 3, 2, 1)

description.plain:
Released as the second single, the music video is almost a parody of Flo Rida’s career. It opens on a private jet, with Flo and a friend on board holding up a Gold plaque and talking about money. Where could the song possibly go from here? Try a pristine beach, with alcohol flowing, a shirtless Flo Rida, and many beautiful women.

Fittingly, it was used at the end of The Hangover Part II, and it was another successful track for Mr. International, charting in 18 countries, and just cracking the Billboard Hot 100 at number 98.
